      'Terminal Emulators': 'Programs that replicate the function of a hardware terminal, providing a text-based interface within a GUI.',
      'GNOME Terminal': 'The default terminal emulator for Ubuntu and other GNOME-based Linux distributions, providing a graphical interface to a Unix shell with multiple tabs, customizable profiles, and keyboard shortcuts. Default shell: Bash.',
      'Terminal': 'The default terminal emulator on macOS, providing a command-line interface to the underlying Unix-like system and supporting shells like Zsh (default) and Bash.',
      'Windows Terminal': 'A modern, tabbed terminal application for Windows that runs multiple shells — Command Prompt, PowerShell, and WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux) — in a single interface with extensive customization options. Default shell: PowerShell.',
      'macOS': "Apple's Unix-based operating system for Mac computers.",
      'Unix': 'A family of multi-user, multitasking operating systems developed at Bell Labs starting in 1969, known for modular design, a powerful command-line interface, and influence on modern systems like Linux and macOS.',
      'File Format': 'The ls -l output format: permissions — user owner — group owner — file size — last modification date/time — file location.',
      'File Permissions': 'A 10-character string: [file type][user rwx/s/S][group rwx/s][other rwx/t]. File type: d (directory), - (regular file). Permission bits: r (read), w (write), x (execute), s (SetUID/SetGID), S (SetUID without execute), t (Sticky — restricts deletion within a directory), - (empty).',
      'Important Files': 'Key Unix/Linux system files and directories that store configuration, user data, and process information.',
      '/etc': 'A directory containing system-wide configuration files and shell scripts used to boot and initialize the system.',
      '/etc/sudoers': 'Lists which users are authorized to run commands with sudo.',
      '/etc/passwd': 'Maps usernames to UIDs and stores user account info. Format: username:password:UID:GID:GECOS:home:shell. Password x means it is stored in /etc/shadow; UID 0 is root.',
      '/etc/shadow': 'Stores encrypted user passwords and password policy details. Format: username:encrypted_password:last_changed:min_days:max_days:warn_days:inactive_days:expire_date:reserved.',
      '/etc/group': 'Defines groups and their members. Format: group_name:password:GID:user_list. Default group password is *; GID 0 is root.',
      '/etc/apt/sources.list': 'Lists the pre-approved sources from which packages can be installed on Debian-based systems.',
      '/proc': 'A virtual filesystem that stores real-time process and kernel information for all currently running processes.',
      'Linux': 'A family of open-source, Unix-like operating systems based on the Linux kernel. Defaults to the Bash shell.',
      'Debian': 'A stable GNU/Linux distribution known for its commitment to free software and robust APT package management.',
      'Ubuntu': 'A popular Linux distribution based on Debian, known for ease of use and broad community support.',
      'Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL)': 'A commercially supported Linux distribution designed for enterprise environments.',
      'Windows': "Microsoft's widely used graphical operating system for personal computers and enterprise servers.",
      'Software Development/Programming': 'The process of designing, writing, testing, and maintaining source code for software applications.',
