      // Big O Notation
      'Big O Notation': 'A mathematical notation describing the upper bound of an algorithm\'s time or space complexity as input size grows.',
      'How Does Performance Scale?': 'The way an algorithm\'s resource usage grows relative to the size of its input.',
      'What Does \'O\' Stand For?': 'The "O" stands for "Order of," referring to the order of growth of an algorithm\'s complexity.',
      'Common Big O Notations (from best to worst performance for large \'n\')': 'The standard set of complexity classes used to classify algorithms from fastest to slowest growth rates.',
      'O(1) - Constant Time': 'An algorithm whose execution time remains the same regardless of input size.',
      'Examples|O(1)': 'Concrete operations that always execute in constant time.',
      'Array index access': 'Accessing an element by its index in an array is always O(1).',
      'Hash table lookup (average)': 'Finding a value by key in a hash table takes O(1) on average.',
      'Checking if a stack is empty': 'Inspecting the size or top of a stack is a single constant-time operation.',
      'Assigning a variable': 'Storing a value in a variable is a single constant-time operation.',
      'Arithmetic operations': 'Basic arithmetic on fixed-size numbers executes in constant time.',
      'O(log n) - Logarithmic Time': 'An algorithm that reduces the problem size by a constant factor each step, growing very slowly with input.',
      'Examples|O(log n)': 'Concrete algorithms that run in logarithmic time.',
      'Binary search': 'Halves the search space each step, achieving O(log n) on sorted arrays.',
      'Operations on a balanced BST': 'Search, insert, and delete on a balanced binary search tree are each O(log n).',
      'O(n) - Linear Time': 'An algorithm whose execution time grows proportionally with input size.',
      'Examples|O(n)': 'Concrete algorithms or operations that run in linear time.',
      'Linear search': 'Scans each element once to find a target, running in O(n).',
      'Traversing an array': 'Visiting every element in an array requires O(n) operations.',
      'Finding min/max in unsorted array': 'Must examine every element to find the minimum or maximum, taking O(n).',
      'Copying an array': 'Duplicating all n elements of an array requires O(n) time.',
      'O(n log n) - Linearithmic Time': 'An algorithm that combines linear and logarithmic work, typical of efficient comparison-based sorting.',
      'Examples|O(n log n)': 'Concrete algorithms that run in linearithmic time.',
      'Merge sort': 'Divides and merges arrays recursively, achieving O(n log n) in all cases.',
      'Heap sort': 'Builds a heap and repeatedly extracts the max/min, running in O(n log n).',
      'O(n^2) - Quadratic Time': 'An algorithm whose execution time grows as the square of the input size, typical of nested loops.',
      'Examples|O(n^2)': 'Concrete algorithms that run in quadratic time.',
      'Bubble sort': 'Repeatedly swaps adjacent elements in nested passes, running in O(n^2).',
      'Selection sort': 'Finds the minimum in each pass with a nested scan, running in O(n^2).',
      'Insertion sort': 'Shifts elements in sorted position using nested iterations, running in O(n^2) worst case.',
      'Nested loops over same array': 'Any algorithm with two nested loops each iterating over n elements runs in O(n^2).',
      'O(2^n) - Exponential Time': 'An algorithm whose execution time doubles with each additional input element, becoming quickly infeasible.',
      'Examples|O(2^n)': 'Concrete algorithms that run in exponential time.',
      'Recursive Fibonacci': 'Naive recursive Fibonacci recomputes subproblems, resulting in O(2^n) calls.',
      'Solving the Tower of Hanoi': 'Requires 2^n - 1 moves to solve n disks, making it O(2^n).',
      'O(n!) - Factorial Time': 'An algorithm whose execution time grows factorially, rendering it practical only for very small inputs.',
      'Examples|O(n!)': 'Concrete algorithms that run in factorial time.',
      'Generating all permutations of a set': 'Producing every ordering of n elements requires n! iterations.',
      'Brute-force Traveling Salesman Problem': 'Checking every possible route through n cities requires evaluating (n-1)! paths.',
      'Why Do We Ignore Constants and Lower-Order Terms?': 'At large input sizes, constants and smaller terms become negligible compared to the dominant growth term.',
      'How to Determine Big O': 'A systematic process for analyzing an algorithm\'s time complexity by identifying its dominant operations.',
      'Identify the Input Size (n)': 'The first step in Big O analysis is defining what n represents for the given algorithm.',
      'Examples|Identify Input Size': 'Common ways n is defined depending on the type of problem.',
      'n = length of array': 'For array-based algorithms, n is typically the number of elements in the array.',
      'n = number of nodes in a graph': 'For graph algorithms, n typically represents the number of vertices.',
